{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/143820.The_Horseman_on_the_Roof", "title": "The Horseman on the Roof", "titleComplete": "The Horseman on the Roof", "description": "Perhaps no other of his novels better reveals Giono's perfect balance between lyricism and narrative, description and characterization, the epic and the particular, than The Horseman on the Roof. This novel, which Giono began writing in 1934 and which was published in 1951, expanded and solidified his reputation as one of Europe's most important writers.This is a novel of adventure, a roman courtois, that tells the story of Angelo, a nobleman who has been forced to leave Italy because of a duel, and is returning to his homeland by way of Provence. But that region is in the grip of a cholera epidemic, travelers are being imprisoned behind barricades, and exposure to the disease is almost certain.Angelo's escapades, adventures, and heroic self-sacrifice in this hot, hallucinatory landscape, among corpses, criminals, and rioting townspeople, share this epic tale.", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1312038325i/143820.jpg", "genres": ["French Literature", "Romance", "Novels", "France", "Historical Fiction", "Classics", "Roman", "Adventure", "20th Century", "Fiction"], "asin": "086547060X", "isbn": "086547060X", "isbn13": "9780865470606", "publisher": "North Point Press", "series": ["Le Cycle du Hussard "], "author": ["Jean Giono", "Jonathan Griffin"], "publishDate": 378720000000, "characters": ["Angelo Pardi", "Giuseppe", "Pauline de Th\u00e9us"], "ratingHistogram": [59, 125, 374, 607, 560], "ratingsCount": 1725, "reviewsCount": 127, "numPages": 426, "language": "English"}
{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/782581.Lorca", "title": "Lorca: Gypsy Ballads (Aris & Phillips Hispanic Classics)", "titleComplete": "Lorca: Gypsy Ballads (Aris & Phillips Hispanic Classics) (Spanish Edition)", "description": "Lorca's famous Gypsy Ballads were composed in the 1920s, when his poetic style was evolving from the traditional towards the surrealist. The combination of the ballad's perennial narrative format with startling and allusive imagery has intrigued readers ever since.", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1178301202i/782581.jpg", "genres": ["Romance", "School", "Literature", "Poetry", "Classics", "Spanish Literature", "Spain", "20th Century", "European Literature", "Fiction"], "asin": "0856684910", "isbn": "0856684910", "isbn13": "9780856684913", "publisher": "Liverpool University Press", "author": ["R. G. Havard", "Robert G. Harvard"], "publishDate": 631180800000, "ratingHistogram": [134, 412, 1711, 3456, 5148], "ratingsCount": 10861, "reviewsCount": 650, "numPages": 174, "language": "Spanish; Castilian"}
{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/396931.The_Origins_of_Totalitarianism", "title": "The Origins of Totalitarianism", "titleComplete": "The Origins of Totalitarianism", "description": "Hannah Arendt's definitive work on totalitarianism and an essential component of any study of twentieth-century political historyThe Origins of Totalitarianism begins with the rise of anti-Semitism in central and western Europe in the 1800s and continues with an examination of European colonial imperialism from 1884 to the outbreak of World War I. Arendt explores the institutions and operations of totalitarian movements, focusing on the two genuine forms of totalitarian government in our time\u2014Nazi Germany and Stalinist Russia\u2014which she adroitly recognizes were two sides of the same coin, rather than opposing philosophies of Right and Left. From this vantage point, she discusses the evolution of classes into masses, the role of propaganda in dealing with the nontotalitarian world, the use of terror, and the nature of isolation and loneliness as preconditions for total domination.", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1565095964i/396931.jpg", "genres": ["Sociology", "Germany", "History", "Psychology", "Nonfiction", "Theory", "Classics", "Politics", "Political Science", "Philosophy"], "publisher": "Harcourt Brace Jovanovich", "author": ["Hannah Arendt"], "publishDate": 94723200000, "ratingHistogram": [130, 339, 1472, 4035, 6103], "ratingsCount": 12079, "reviewsCount": 1013, "numPages": 527, "language": "English", "awards": [{"name": "National Book Award Finalist", "awardedAt": -568051200000, "category": "Nonfiction", "hasWon": null}]}
{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/28293.Life", "title": "Life: A User's Manual", "titleComplete": "Life: A User's Manual", "description": "Life: A User's Manual is an unclassified masterpiece, a sprawling compendium as encyclopedic as Dante's Commedia and Chaucer's Canterbury Tales and, in its break with tradition, as inspiring as Joyce's Ulysses. Perec's spellbinding puzzle begins in an apartment block in the XVIIth arrondissement of Paris where, chapter by chapter, room by room, like an onion being peeled, an extraordinary rich cast of characters is revealed in a series of tales that are bizarre, unlikely, moving, funny, or (sometimes) quite ordinary. From the confessions of a racing cyclist to the plans of an avenging murderer, from a young ethnographer obsessed with a Sumatran tribe to the death of a trapeze artist, from the fears of an ex-croupier to the dreams of a sex-change pop star to an eccentric English millionaire who has devised the ultimate pastime, Life is a manual of human irony, portraying the mixed marriages of fortunes, passions and despairs, betrayals and bereavements, of hundreds of lives in Paris and around the world.But the novel is more than an extraordinary range of fictions; it is a closely observed account of life and experience. The apartment block's one hundred rooms are arranged in a magic square, and the book as a whole is peppered with a staggering range of literary puzzles and allusions, acrostics, problems of chess and logic, crosswords, and mathematical formulae. All are there for the reader to solve in the best tradition of the detective novel.", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1651520103i/28293.jpg", "genres": ["French Literature", "Novels", "France", "Literature", "Classics", "Literary Fiction", "20th Century", "Fiction", "Philosophy", "Contemporary"], "asin": "0879237511", "isbn": "0879237511", "isbn13": "9780879237516", "publisher": "David R. Godine, Publisher", "author": ["David Bellos", "Georges Perec"], "publishDate": 591692400000, "characters": ["Bartlebooth"], "places": ["Paris"], "ratingHistogram": [194, 446, 1289, 2555, 4460], "ratingsCount": 8944, "reviewsCount": 882, "numPages": 581, "language": "English", "awards": [{"name": "Prix M\u00e9dicis", "awardedAt": 252489600000, "category": "", "hasWon": null}, {"name": "Mekka-prijs", "awardedAt": 820483200000, "category": null, "hasWon": null}, {"name": "French-American Foundation Translation Prize", "awardedAt": 568022400000, "category": "Fiction", "hasWon": null}, {"name": "Met\u0173 verstin\u0117 knyga", "awardedAt": 1672560000000, "category": "Fiction", "hasWon": null}]}
{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/580449.The_Resistible_Rise_of_Arturo_Ui", "title": "The Resistible Rise of Arturo Ui", "titleComplete": "The Resistible Rise of Arturo Ui", "description": "The Resistible Rise of Arturo Ui, (Der aufhaltsame Aufstieg des Arturo Ui) was written by the great German dramatist Bertolt Brecht over the course of 3 furious weeks in 1941, while a refugee in Helsinki, Finland. A dizzyingly intelligent political satire on the (ir)resistibleness of political thuggery, Arturo Ui satirizes the rise of Hitler in Nazi Germany by dressing it up as \u201cthe gangster film\u201d we thought we knew. In Arturo Ui, the metamorphosis of thug-to-politician through corruption, intimidation and all manner of brutality is thinly masked by a Chicago gangland epic where the young Arturo Ui stages a violent takeover of the green grocer trade.", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1388986948i/580449.jpg", "genres": ["Germany", "School", "Theatre", "Drama", "Classics", "20th Century", "German Literature", "Politics", "Plays", "Fiction"], "asin": "1559705434", "isbn": "1559705434", "isbn13": "9781559705431", "publisher": "Arcade Publishing", "author": ["Bertolt Brecht"], "publishDate": 981878400000, "places": ["Chicago, Illinois"], "ratingHistogram": [60, 150, 577, 876, 638], "ratingsCount": 2301, "reviewsCount": 108, "numPages": 125, "language": "English", "awards": [{"name": "Schlegel-Tieck Prize", "awardedAt": 220953600000, "category": "Ralph Manheim", "hasWon": null}]}
{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/1393713.La_Confusion_des_sentiments", "title": "La Confusion des sentiments", "titleComplete": "La Confusion des sentiments", "description": "Au soir de sa vie, un vieux professeur se souvient de l'aventure qui, plus que les honneurs et la r\u00e9ussite de sa carri\u00e8re, a marqu\u00e9 sa vie. A dix-neuf ans, il a \u00e9t\u00e9 fascin\u00e9 par la personnalit\u00e9 d'un de ses professeurs ; l'admiration et la recherche inconsciente d'un P\u00e8re font alors na\u00eetre en lui un sentiment m\u00eal\u00e9 d'idol\u00e2trie, de soumission et d'un amour presque morbide. Freud a salu\u00e9 la finesse et la v\u00e9rit\u00e9 avec laquelle l'auteur d'Amok et du Joueur d'\u00e9checs restituait le trouble d'une passion et le malaise qu'elle engendre chez celui qui en est l'objet. Paru en 1926, ce r\u00e9cit bref et profond connut un succ\u00e8s fulgurant, en raison de la nouveaut\u00e9 audacieuse du sujet. Il demeure assur\u00e9ment l'un des chefs-d'\u0153uvre du grand \u00e9crivain autrichien.", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1319309887i/1393713.jpg", "genres": ["LGBT", "Germany", "Short Stories", "Novels", "Literature", "Classics", "Novella", "20th Century", "German Literature", "Fiction"], "asin": "2253061433", "isbn": "2253061433", "isbn13": "9782253061434", "publisher": "Le Livre de Poche", "author": ["Stefan Zweig"], "publishDate": 1222844400000, "characters": ["Roland"], "ratingHistogram": [187, 437, 1929, 3889, 3613], "ratingsCount": 10055, "reviewsCount": 1027, "numPages": 124, "language": "French"}
{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/70105.The_Counterfeiters", "title": "The Counterfeiters", "titleComplete": "The Counterfeiters", "description": "Originally published in 1925, this book became known for the frank sexuality of its contents and its account of middle class French morality. The themes of the book explore the problem of morals, the problem of society and the problems facing writers. An appendix to this edition (Vintage, 1973) contains excerpts from the Gide's notebooks which he kept while writing this book.", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1632035613i/70105.jpg", "genres": ["LGBT", "French Literature", "Novels", "France", "Literature", "Nobel Prize", "Classics", "Queer", "20th Century", "Fiction"], "asin": "0394718429", "isbn": "0394718429", "isbn13": "9780394718422", "publisher": "Vintage", "author": ["Andr\u00e9 Gide"], "publishDate": 108716400000, "places": ["France", "Paris"], "ratingHistogram": [241, 681, 2290, 3308, 2845], "ratingsCount": 9365, "reviewsCount": 455, "numPages": 451, "language": "English"}
{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/771287.The_Wonderful_Adventures_of_Nils", "title": "The Wonderful Adventures of Nils", "titleComplete": "The Wonderful Adventures of Nils", "description": "Winner of the Nobel Prize for Literature in 1909 \u2014 the first woman to be so honored \u2014 Swedish novelist Selma Lagerl\u00f6f (1858\u20131940) was a gifted storyteller whose writings were often tinged with the supernatural and rooted in the sagas and legends of her homeland.She secured her reputation as a children's-book author with The Wonderful Adventures of Nils , long considered a masterpiece of children's literature. Written at the request of Swedish school authorities and first published in 1906, it is the enchanting and remarkably original tale of Nils Holgersson, a mischievous boy of 14 who is changed by an elf into a tiny being able to understand the speech of birds and animals.Brilliantly weaving fact and fiction into a breathtaking and beautiful fable, the story recounts Nils's adventures as he is transported over the countryside on the back of a goose. From this vantage point, Nils witnesses a host of events that provide young readers with an abundance of information about nature, geography, folklore, animal life, and more.Reset in easy-to-read type and enhanced with 10 new illustrations, this inexpensive, unabridged edition will bring new generations of readers under the magical spell of a timeless classic.", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1293569262i/771287.jpg", "genres": ["Animals", "Sweden", "Childrens", "Scandinavian Literature", "Nobel Prize", "Classics", "Fantasy", "Adventure", "Swedish Literature", "Fiction"], "asin": "0486286118", "isbn": "0486286118", "isbn13": "9780486286112", "publisher": "Dover Publications", "series": ["Nils Holgersson"], "author": ["Velma Swanston Howard", "Selma Lagerl\u00f6f", "Mustafa Yal\u00e7\u0131ner", "Thea Kliros", "Peter Klusen", "Mathilde Mann"], "publishDate": 803026800000, "characters": ["Kebnekaise", "Clement Larsson", "Grayskin", "Smirre Fox", "Thumbietot", "Bataki", "Rosenbom", "Morten Goosey-gander", "Crawlie", "Takern", "Dunfin", "Mother Bear", "Lake M\u00e4lar"], "places": ["Ottenby", "Sweden", "Karlskrona", "V\u00e4stra Vemmenh\u00f6g"], "ratingHistogram": [166, 582, 2460, 3992, 4530], "ratingsCount": 11730, "reviewsCount": 604, "numPages": 219, "language": "English"}
{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/119561.The_Order_of_Things", "title": "The Order of Things: An Archaeology of the Human Sciences", "titleComplete": "The Order of Things: An Archaeology of the Human Sciences", "description": "Librarian note: an alternate cover for this edition can be found here.With vast erudition, Foucault cuts across disciplines and reaches back into seventeenth century to show how classical systems of knowledge, which linked all of nature within a great chain of being and analogies between the stars in the heavens and the features in a human face, gave way to the modern sciences of biology, philology, and political economy. The result is nothing less than an archaeology of the sciences that unearths old patterns of meaning and reveals the shocking arbitrariness of our received truths.In the work that established him as the most important French thinker since Sartre, Michel Foucault offers startling evidence that \u201cman\u201d\u2014man as a subject of scientific knowledge\u2014is at best a recent invention, the result of a fundamental mutation in our culture.", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1486658551i/119561.jpg", "genres": ["Sociology", "History", "France", "Science", "Nonfiction", "Theory", "Psychology", "Academic", "Anthropology", "Philosophy"], "asin": "0679753354", "isbn": "0679753354", "isbn13": "9780679753353", "publisher": "Vintage", "author": ["Michel Foucault"], "publishDate": 764928000000, "ratingHistogram": [147, 361, 1560, 3153, 3831], "ratingsCount": 9052, "reviewsCount": 305, "numPages": 416, "language": "English"}
{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/283901.Tristes_Tropiques", "title": "Tristes Tropiques", "titleComplete": "Tristes Tropiques", "description": "Tristes Tropiques begins with the line \u2018I hate travelling and explorers\u2019, yet during his life Claude L\u00e9vi-Strauss travelled from wartime France to the Amazon basin and the dense upland jungles of Brazil, where he found \u2018human society reduced to its most basic expression\u2019. His account of the people he encountered changed the field of anthropology, transforming Western notions of \u2018primitive\u2019 man. Tristes Tropiques is a major work of art as well as of scholarship. It is a memoir of exquisite beauty and a masterpiece of travel writing: funny, discursive, movingly detailing personal and cultural loss, and brilliantly connecting disparate fields of thought. Few books have had as powerful and broad an impact.", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1302750303i/283901.jpg", "genres": ["Sociology", "Memoir", "History", "France", "Science", "Nonfiction", "Travel", "Classics", "Anthropology", "Philosophy"], "asin": "0140165622", "isbn": "0140165622", "isbn13": "9780140165623", "publisher": "Penguin", "author": ["Doreen Weightman", "Claude L\u00e9vi-Strauss", "John Weightman"], "publishDate": 712652400000, "ratingHistogram": [34, 125, 651, 1321, 1523], "ratingsCount": 3654, "reviewsCount": 258, "numPages": 417, "language": "English", "awards": [{"name": "Scott Moncrieff Prize", "awardedAt": 126259200000, "category": "John Weightman & Doreen Weightman", "hasWon": null}]}
{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/31072.Under_the_Volcano", "title": "Under the Volcano", "titleComplete": "Under the Volcano", "description": "Geoffrey Firmin, a former British consul, has come to Quauhnahuac, Mexico. His debilitating malaise is drinking, an activity that has overshadowed his life. On the most fateful day of the consul's life\u2014the Day of the Dead\u2014his wife, Yvonne, arrives in Quauhnahuac, inspired by a vision of life together away from Mexico and the circumstances that have driven their relationship to the brink of collapse. She is determined to rescue Firmin and their failing marriage, but her mission is further complicated by the presence of Hugh, the consul's half brother, and Jacques, a childhood friend. The events of this one significant day unfold against an unforgettable backdrop of a Mexico at once magical and diabolical.Under the Volcano remains one of literature's most powerful and lyrical statements on the human condition, and a brilliant portrayal of one man's constant struggle against the elemental forces that threaten to destroy him.", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1390014193i/31072.jpg", "genres": ["British Literature", "Novels", "Literature", "Classics", "Historical Fiction", "Literary Fiction", "20th Century", "English Literature", "Fiction", "Unfinished"], "asin": "0060955228", "isbn": "0060955228", "isbn13": "9780060955229", "publisher": "Harper Perennial", "author": ["Malcolm Lowry"], "publishDate": 956732400000, "characters": ["Hugh Firmin", "Jacques Laruelle", "Yvonne Constable", "Geoffrey Firmin"], "places": ["Mexico", "Quauhnahuac"], "ratingHistogram": [1148, 2523, 5543, 7421, 8253], "ratingsCount": 24888, "reviewsCount": 1824, "numPages": 423, "language": "English"}
{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/85410.Three_Essays_on_the_Theory_of_Sexuality", "title": "Three Essays on the Theory of Sexuality", "titleComplete": "Three Essays on the Theory of Sexuality", "description": "The standard edition of Freud's seminal theory of the psychology of sexualityThese three essays -- \"The Sexual Aberrations,\" \"Infantile Sexuality,\" and \"The Transformations of Puberty\" -- are among Sigmund Freud's most important works. Here, Freud outlines the core features of libido theory, his grand view of the psychology of sexuality: sexual perversion is a matter of human nature and \"normal\" sexual behavior only appears later in life, sexual urges begin in infancy, and these urges turn their attention outward as we mature through puberty.Freud first wrote Three Essays on the Theory of Sexuality in 1905 and spent the next two decades making major revisions to the text. This edition offers Freud's complete vision of the sexual self, in the definitive James Strachey translation.", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1329053933i/85410.jpg", "genres": ["Sexuality", "Psychology", "Nonfiction", "Theory", "Science", "Classics", "Essays", "German Literature", "Psychoanalysis", "Philosophy"], "asin": "0465097081", "isbn": "0465097081", "isbn13": "9780465097081", "publisher": "Basic Books", "author": ["James Strachey", "Steven Marcus", "Sigmund Freud"], "publishDate": 950860800000, "ratingHistogram": [215, 636, 2258, 2316, 1651], "ratingsCount": 7076, "reviewsCount": 452, "numPages": 240, "language": "English"}
{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/69880.The_Lost_Honor_of_Katharina_Blum", "title": "The Lost Honor of Katharina Blum", "titleComplete": "The Lost Honor of Katharina Blum", "description": "In an era in which journalists will stop at nothing to break a big story, Henrich B\u00f6ll's The Lost Honor of Katharina Blum has taken on heightened relevance. A young woman's association with a hunted man makes her the target of a journalist determined to grab the headlines by portraying her as an evil woman. As the attacks on her escalate and she becomes the victim of anonymous threats, Katharina sees only one way out of her nightmare.Turning the mystery genre on its head, the novel begins with the confession of a crime, drawing the reader into a web of sensationalism, character assassination, and the unavoidable eruption of violence.", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1338908394i/69880.jpg", "genres": ["Germany", "Crime", "School", "Novels", "Literature", "Nobel Prize", "Classics", "20th Century", "German Literature", "Fiction"], "asin": "0140187286", "isbn": "0140187286", "isbn13": "9780140187281", "publisher": "Penguin Classics", "author": ["Heinrich B\u00f6ll", "Leila Vennewitz"], "publishDate": 770454000000, "characters": ["Dr. Hubert Blorna", "Katharina Blum", "Werner T\u00f6tges", "Walter M\u00f6ding", "Erwin Beizmenne", "Alois Str\u00e4ubleder", "Ludwig G\u00f6tten", "Trude Blorna", "Else Woltersheim"], "places": ["Germany"], "ratingHistogram": [328, 1252, 4647, 6228, 3214], "ratingsCount": 15669, "reviewsCount": 1030, "numPages": 140, "language": "English"}
{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/28369.Zazie_in_the_Metro", "title": "Zazie in the Metro", "titleComplete": "Zazie in the Metro", "description": "Impish, foul-mouthed Zazie arrives in Paris from the country to stay with her uncle Gabriel. All she really wants to do is ride the metro, but finding it shut because of a strike, Zazie looks for other means of amusement and is soon caught up in a comic adventure that becomes wilder and more manic by the minute. In 1960 Queneau's cult classic was made into a hugely successful film by Louis Malle. Packed full of word play and phonetic games, 'Zazie in the Metro' remains as stylish and witty today as it did back then.", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1327953179i/28369.jpg", "genres": ["French Literature", "Novels", "France", "Literature", "Classics", "Roman", "20th Century", "Humor", "Fiction", "Contemporary"], "asin": "0142180041", "isbn": "0142180041", "isbn13": "9780142180044", "publisher": "Penguin Books Ltd", "author": ["Barbara Wright", "Raymond Queneau", "Gilbert Adair"], "publishDate": 1004601600000, "characters": ["Mado-p'tits pieds", "Gabriel", "Charles", "Turandot", "Marceline", "Zazie", "Laverture"], "places": ["Paris"], "ratingHistogram": [280, 835, 2372, 2950, 2043], "ratingsCount": 8480, "reviewsCount": 627, "numPages": 157, "language": "English"}
{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/110457.Nadja", "title": "Nadja", "titleComplete": "Nadja", "description": "Nadja, originally published in France in 1928, is the first and perhaps best Surrealist romance ever written, a book which defined that movement's attitude toward everyday life.The principal narrative is an account of the author's relationship with a girl in the city of Paris, the story of an obsessional presence haunting his life. The first-person narrative is supplemented by forty-four photographs which form an integral part of the work -- pictures of various surreal people, places, and objects which the author visits or is haunted by in naja's presence and which inspire him to mediate on their reality or lack of it. The Nadja of the book is a girl, but, like Bertrand Russell's definition of electricity as not so much a thing as a way things happen, Nadja is not so much a person as the way she makes people behave. She has been described as a state of mind, a feeling about reality, k a kind of vision, and the reader sometimes wonders whether she exists at all. yet it is Nadja who gives form and structure to the novel.", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1693303068i/110457.jpg", "genres": ["French Literature", "Romance", "Novels", "France", "Literature", "Classics", "Art", "20th Century", "Surreal", "Fiction"], "asin": "0802150268", "isbn": "0802150268", "isbn13": "9780802150264", "publisher": "Grove Press", "author": ["Andr\u00e9 Breton", "Richard Howard"], "publishDate": 758275200000, "places": ["Paris"], "ratingHistogram": [443, 1267, 3503, 3550, 2404], "ratingsCount": 11167, "reviewsCount": 905, "numPages": 160, "language": "English"}
{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/252.Sexus", "title": "Sexus", "titleComplete": "Sexus (The Rosy Crucifixion, #1)", "description": "Sexus is the first volume of the scandalous trilogy The Rosy Crucifixion, Henry Miller's major life workHenry Miller called the end of his life in America and the start of a new, bohemian existence in 1930s Paris his 'rosy crucifixion'. His searing fictionalized autobiography of this time of liberation was banned for nearly twenty years. Sexus, the first volume in The Rosy Crucifixion trilogy, looks back to his early sexual escapades in Brooklyn, and his growing infatuation with the playful, teasing dance hall hostess who will become the great obsession of his life.", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1281419601i/252.jpg", "genres": ["Romance", "American", "Novels", "Literature", "Classics", "Roman", "20th Century", "Erotica", "Fiction", "The United States Of America"], "asin": "0802151809", "isbn": "0802151809", "isbn13": "9780802151803", "publisher": "Grove Press", "series": ["The Rosy Crucifixion"], "author": ["Henry Miller"], "publishDate": 758361600000, "ratingHistogram": [179, 525, 1832, 3446, 3527], "ratingsCount": 9509, "reviewsCount": 429, "numPages": 506, "language": "English"}
{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/953435.L_uvre_au_noir", "title": "L'\u0152uvre au noir", "titleComplete": "L'\u0152uvre au noir", "description": "En cr\u00e9ant le personnage de Z\u00e9non, alchimiste et m\u00e9decin du XVIe si\u00e8cle, Marguerite Yourcenar, l'auteure des M\u00e9moires d'Hadrien, ne raconte pas seulement le destin tragique d'un homme extraordinaire. C'est toute une \u00e9poque qui revit dans son infinie richesse, comme aussi dans son \u00e2cre et brutale r\u00e9alit\u00e9 ; un monde contrast\u00e9 o\u00f9 s'affrontent le Moyen Age et la Renaissance, et o\u00f9 pointent d\u00e9j\u00e0 les temps modernes, monde dont Z\u00e9non est issu, mais dont peu \u00e0 peu cet homme libre se d\u00e9gage, et qui pour cette raison m\u00eame finira par le broyer.", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1368219574i/953435.jpg", "genres": ["French Literature", "Historical", "Novels", "France", "Literature", "Historical Fiction", "Classics", "Roman", "Belgium", "Fiction"], "asin": "2070367983", "isbn": "2070367983", "isbn13": "9782070367986", "publisher": "Gallimard", "author": ["Marguerite Yourcenar"], "publishDate": 204534000000, "ratingHistogram": [107, 309, 921, 1816, 2070], "ratingsCount": 5223, "reviewsCount": 396, "numPages": 480, "language": "French", "awards": [{"name": "Prix Femina", "awardedAt": -63129600000, "category": "", "hasWon": null}, {"name": "Nagrada Milo\u0161 N.\u0110uri\u0107", "awardedAt": 126259200000, "category": null, "hasWon": null}]}
{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/12095.The_Bald_Soprano_and_Other_Plays", "title": "The Bald Soprano and Other Plays", "titleComplete": "The Bald Soprano and Other Plays", "description": "The leading figure of absurdist theater and one of the great innovators of the modern stage, Eugene Ionesco (1909-94) did not write his first play, The Bald Soprano, until 1950. He went on to become an internationally renowned master of modern drama, famous for the comic proportions and bizarre effects that allow his work to be simultaneously hilarious, tragic, and profound. As Ionesco has said, \"Theater is not literature. . . . It is simply what cannot be expressed by any other means.\"", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1699993585i/12095.jpg", "genres": ["French Literature", "Theatre", "Drama", "France", "Romanian Literature", "Literature", "Classics", "20th Century", "Plays", "Fiction"], "asin": "0802130798", "isbn": "0802130798", "isbn13": "9780802130792", "publisher": "Grove Press", "author": ["Donald M. Allen", "Eug\u00e8ne Ionesco"], "publishDate": 378720000000, "ratingHistogram": [103, 336, 1182, 2210, 2373], "ratingsCount": 6204, "reviewsCount": 165, "numPages": 160, "language": "English"}
