{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/17716.Waiting_for_Godot", "title": "Waiting for Godot", "titleComplete": "Waiting for Godot", "description": "The story revolves around two seemingly homeless men simply waiting for someone\u2014or something\u2014named Godot. Vladimir and Estragon wait near a tree, inhabiting a drama spun of their own consciousness. The result is a comical wordplay of poetry, dreamscapes, and nonsense, which has been interpreted as mankind\u2019s inexhaustible search for meaning. Beckett\u2019s language pioneered an expressionistic minimalism that captured the existential post-World War II Europe. His play remains one of the most magical and beautiful allegories of our time.", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1327910301i/17716.jpg", "genres": ["School", "Theatre", "Drama", "Literature", "France", "Classics", "Irish Literature", "Plays", "Fiction", "Philosophy"], "publisher": "Grove", "author": ["Samuel Beckett"], "publishDate": 1293868800000, "characters": ["Estragon", "boy", "Lucky", "Pozzo", "Vladimir (Samuel Beckett)"], "ratingHistogram": [7926, 16224, 43237, 65421, 67475], "ratingsCount": 200283, "reviewsCount": 8705, "numPages": 109, "language": "English"}
{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/8921.The_Hound_of_the_Baskervilles", "title": "The Hound of the Baskervilles", "titleComplete": "The Hound of the Baskervilles (Sherlock Holmes, #5)", "description": "In this, one of the most famous of Doyle's mysteries, the tale of an ancient curse and a savage ghostly hound comes frighteningly to life. The gray towers of Baskerville Hall and the wild open country of Dartmoor will haunt the reader as Holmes and Watson seek to unravel the many secrets of the misty English bogs.", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1355929358i/8921.jpg", "genres": ["British Literature", "Crime", "Fiction", "Novels", "Thriller", "Literature", "Classics", "Audiobook", "Mystery", "Mystery Thriller"], "publisher": "Signet", "series": ["Sherlock Holmes Compleet", "Sherlock Holmes"], "author": ["Mark Hallaq", "Anne Perry", "Arthur Conan Doyle", "L\u00edgia Junqueira"], "publishDate": 993970800000, "characters": ["John Clayton", "Mr. Frankland", "Mr. Selden", "John Watson", "Dr. John Watson", "Mr. Perkins", "James Mortimer", "Henry Baskerville", "Laura Lyons", "Eliza Barrymore", "Jack Stapleton", "James Desmond", "Sherlock Holmes", "John Barrymore (Conan Doyle)", "Charles Baskerville", "Beryl Stapleton"], "places": ["Dartmoor, Devon, England", "Devon, England", "England", "London, England"], "ratingHistogram": [2366, 9362, 61769, 136120, 133267], "ratingsCount": 342884, "reviewsCount": 12201, "numPages": 256, "language": "English", "awards": [{"name": "Audie Award", "awardedAt": 1420099200000, "category": "Best Audio Drama", "hasWon": null}, {"name": "CWA Best Ever", "awardedAt": 1357027200000, "category": "Crime Novel", "hasWon": null}]}
{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/46170.For_Whom_the_Bell_Tolls", "title": "For Whom the Bell Tolls", "titleComplete": "For Whom the Bell Tolls", "description": "In 1937 Ernest Hemingway traveled to Spain to cover the civil war there for the North American Newspaper Alliance. Three years later he completed the greatest novel to emerge from \"the good fight,\" For Whom the Bell Tolls. The story of Robert Jordan, a young American in the International Brigades attached to an antifascist guerilla unit in the mountains of Spain, it tells of loyalty and courage, love and defeat, and the tragic death of an ideal. In his portrayal of Jordan's love for the beautiful Maria and his superb account of El Sordo's last stand, in his brilliant travesty of La Pasionaria and his unwillingness to believe in blind faith, Hemingway surpasses his achievement in The Sun Also Rises and A Farewell to Arms to create a work at once rare and beautiful, strong and brutal, compassionate, moving and wise. \"If the function of a writer is to reveal reality,\" Maxwell Perkins wrote to Hemingway after reading the manuscript, \"no one ever so completely performed it.\" Greater in power, broader in scope, and more intensely emotional than any of the author's previous works, it stands as one of the best war novels of all time.", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1492591524i/46170.jpg", "genres": ["Classic Literature", "American", "Novels", "Literature", "War", "Classics", "Historical Fiction", "Literary Fiction", "Spain", "Fiction"], "publisher": "Scribner", "author": ["Ernest Hemingway"], "publishDate": 788947200000, "characters": ["Maria", "Robert Jordan", "Pilar", "Pablo Saler", "Anselmo", "El Sordo"], "places": ["Spain"], "ratingHistogram": [6106, 16178, 59112, 106941, 103843], "ratingsCount": 292180, "reviewsCount": 8886, "numPages": 471, "language": "English"}
{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/18796.In_Search_of_Lost_Time", "title": "In Search of Lost Time", "titleComplete": "In Search of Lost Time", "description": "On the surface a traditional \"Bildungsroman\" describing the narrator\u2019s journey of self-discovery, this huge and complex book is also a panoramic and richly comic portrait of France in the author\u2019s lifetime, and a profound meditation on the nature of art, love, time, memory and death. But for most readers it is the characters of the novel who loom the largest: Swann and Odette, Monsieur de Charlus, Morel, the Duchesse de Guermantes, Fran\u00e7oise, Saint-Loup and so many others \u2014 Giants, as the author calls them, immersed in Time. \"In Search of Lost Time\" is a novel in seven volumes. The novel began to take shape in 1909. Proust continued to work on it until his final illness in the autumn of 1922 forced him to break off. Proust established the structure early on, but even after volumes were initially finished he kept adding new material, and edited one volume after another for publication. The last three of the seven volumes contain oversights and fragmentary or unpolished passages as they existed in draft form at the death of the author; the publication of these parts was overseen by his brother Robert.For this authoritative English-language edition, D. J. Enright has revised the late Terence Kilmartin\u2019s acclaimed reworking of C. K. Scott Moncrieff\u2019s translation to take into account the new definitive French editions of \u00c0 la recherche du temps perdu (the final volume of these new editions was published by the Biblioth\u00e8que de la Pl\u00e9iade in 1989).", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1657567516i/18796.jpg", "genres": ["Classic Literature", "French Literature", "Novels", "France", "Literature", "Classics", "Literary Fiction", "20th Century", "Fiction", "Philosophy"], "asin": "0812969642", "isbn": "0812969642", "isbn13": "9780812969641", "publisher": "Modern Library", "author": ["C.K. Scott Moncrieff", "Marcel Proust", "Andreas Mayor", "Terence Kilmartin", "D.J. Enright"], "publishDate": 1054623600000, "ratingHistogram": [332, 482, 1313, 2800, 7626], "ratingsCount": 12553, "reviewsCount": 841, "numPages": 4211, "language": "English"}
{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/426504.Ficciones", "title": "Ficciones", "titleComplete": "Ficciones", "description": "The seventeen pieces in Ficciones demonstrate the whirlwind of Borges's genius and mirror the precision and potency of his intellect and inventiveness, his piercing irony, his skepticism, and his obsession with fantasy. Borges sends us on a journey into a compelling, bizarre, and profoundly resonant realm; we enter the fearful sphere of Pascal's abyss, the surreal and literal labyrinth of books, and the iconography of eternal return. To enter the worlds in Ficciones is to enter the mind of Jorge Luis Borges, wherein lies Heaven, Hell, and everything else in between. Part One: The Garden of Forking Paths Prologue Tl\u00f6n, Uqbar, Orbis Tertius (1940) The Approach to Al-Mu'tasim (1936, not included in the 1941 edition) Pierre Menard, Author of the Quixote (1939) The Circular Ruins (1940) The Lottery in Babylon (1941) An Examination of the Work of Herbert Quain (1941) The Library of Babel (1941) The Garden of Forking Paths (1941) Part Two: Artifices Prologue Funes the Memorious (1942) The Form of the Sword (1942) Theme of the Traitor and the Hero (1944) Death and the Compass (1942) The Secret Miracle (1943) Three Versions of Judas (1944) The End (1953, 2nd edition only) The Sect of the Phoenix (1952, 2nd edition only) The South (1953, 2nd edition only)", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1621713120i/426504.jpg", "genres": ["Latin American", "Short Stories", "Literature", "Classics", "Fantasy", "Spanish Literature", "20th Century", "Magical Realism", "Fiction", "Philosophy"], "asin": "0802130305", "isbn": "0802130305", "isbn13": "9780802130303", "publisher": "Grove Press", "author": ["Jorge Luis Borges", "Anthony Kerrigan", "Anthony Bonner"], "publishDate": 760089600000, "ratingHistogram": [661, 1766, 6631, 17860, 40219], "ratingsCount": 67137, "reviewsCount": 4166, "numPages